      <akn:section eId="sec_38_2431">
        <akn:num>38-2431</akn:num>
        <akn:heading>Findings.</akn:heading>
<akn:subsection eId="subsec_38-2431_a">
      <akn:num>(a)</akn:num>
      <akn:content><akn:p>American Sign Language (“ASL”) is one of the top 4 widely used languages in the United States and Canada.</akn:p></akn:content>
    </akn:subsection><akn:subsection eId="subsec_38-2431_b">
      <akn:num>(b)</akn:num>
      <akn:content><akn:p>The District of Columbia has over 20,000 deaf and hard of hearing residents, many of whom use ASL as their primary language.</akn:p></akn:content>
    </akn:subsection><akn:subsection eId="subsec_38-2431_c">
      <akn:num>(c)</akn:num>
      <akn:content><akn:p>ASL has met the accepted linguistic criteria to qualify as a legitimate language in that it has a system of arbitrary symbols, grammatical signals, syntax, has a community of users, and it has undergone historical changes.</akn:p></akn:content>
    </akn:subsection><akn:subsection eId="subsec_38-2431_d">
      <akn:num>(d)</akn:num>
      <akn:content><akn:p>Two-thirds of state legislatures in the United States recognize and accept ASL as a bona fide language.</akn:p></akn:content>
    </akn:subsection>
      </akn:section>
